SIMPLE: essence
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Essence
<hw>Es"sence</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>essence</ets>, L. <ets>essentia</ets>, formed as if fr. a p. pr. of
<ets>esse</ets> to be. See <er>Is</er>, and cf. <er>Entity</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The constituent elementary notions which constitute a
complex notion, and must be enumerated to define it; sometimes called
the <xex>nominal essence</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The constituent quality or qualities which belong to
any object, or class of objects, or on which they depend for being what
they are (distinguished as <xex>real essence</xex>); the real being,
divested of all logical accidents; that quality which constitutes or
marks the true nature of anything; distinctive character; hence, virtue
or quality of a thing, separated from its grosser parts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The laws are at present, both in form and <qex>essence</qex>, the
greatest curse that society labors under.</q>
<rj><qau>Landor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gifts and alms are the expressions, not the <qex>essence</qex> of
this virtue [charity].</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>essence</qex> of Addison's humor is irony.</q>
<rj><qau>Courthope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Constituent substance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And uncompounded is their <qex>essence</qex> pure.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A being; esp., a purely spiritual being.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As far as gods and heavenly <qex>essences</qex>⟦br⟧
Can perish.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had been indulging in fanciful speculations on spiritual
<qex>essences</qex>, until . . . he had and ideal world of his own
around him.</q> <rj><qau>W. Irving.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The predominant qualities or virtues of a plant or
drug, extracted and refined from grosser matter; or, more strictly, the
solution in spirits of wine of a volatile or essential oil; <as>as, the
<ex>essence</ex> of mint, and the like</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The . . . word <qex>essence</qex> . . . scarcely underwent a more
complete transformation when from being the abstract of the verb
⟦ldquo⟧to be,⟦rdquo⟧ it came to denote something sufficiently concrete
to be inclosed in a glass bottle.</q> <rj><qau>J. S.
Mill.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Perfume; odor; scent; or the volatile matter
constituting perfume.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nor let the <qex>essences</qex> exhale.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Essence</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Essence
<hw>Es"sence</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Essenced</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Essencing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <def>To perfume; to
scent.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Essenced</xex> fops.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Essene</ent>⟦br⟧
